  <!-- FORMBY WARRANTY SECTION, UNIQUE -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="pf-section-label">FORMBY PROPERTY KNOWLEDGE</span>
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">Why Formby Homeowners Need a Power Flush Report More Than Most</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Formby's larger homes, newer boilers and higher property values make boiler warranty protection more financially significant here than in most Merseyside locations. A written power flush report is not just a maintenance record, it is the document that protects a 10-year manufacturer warranty worth thousands of pounds.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Formby's Boiler Fleet Is Newer and More Expensive Than Most of Merseyside</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Formby has a high proportion of Worcester Bosch and Vaillant boilers installed in the last 5 to 12 years. Many were installed with extended 10-year warranties when the property was upgraded or renovated. These are expensive appliances, a Worcester Bosch Greenstar 8000 or a Vaillant ecoTEC Plus is worth £1,500 to £2,500 as an appliance alone before installation costs. If the system it was connected to was not clean at installation, or if sludge has since built up to the point where it causes a heat exchanger failure, the manufacturer can reject the warranty claim on the grounds that the contaminated system caused the damage. A written power flush report from a Gas Safe registered engineer is your evidence that the system was properly maintained. Without it, you may be facing a heat exchanger replacement or new boiler at your own cost despite being within the warranty period.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Larger Formby Systems Lose More Efficiency from Sludge Build-Up</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">A typical Formby 4-bed detached property has 12 to 15 radiators. A 15 to 25% efficiency loss from sludge contamination on a 14-radiator system running over a full Merseyside winter is a meaningfully larger financial impact than the same efficiency loss on a 7-radiator Liverpool terrace. If your Formby home takes noticeably longer to reach temperature than it did when the system was installed, or if some radiators in the larger rooms are not delivering full heat, sludge restriction is the most likely cause. A power flush typically restores the full heat output within hours of completion. Many Formby homeowners who have had a power flush report lower heating bills in the month following the job.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Zone Circuits and Underfloor Areas Require Individual Flushing</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Many Formby properties have multi-zone heating systems with separate circuits for upstairs and downstairs, or underfloor heating circuits in kitchen extensions and renovation areas. A power flush on a multi-zone system must flush each zone circuit individually with the zone valve open for that circuit and closed for others. An engineer who attempts to flush all zones simultaneously will deliver a partial result on each zone. We flush zone-controlled Formby systems correctly, each zone in turn, each radiator within that zone individually. For properties with underfloor circuits, the underfloor manifold and each underfloor loop is flushed separately. This takes additional time but delivers a complete result across every part of the system.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- SIGNS -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">Signs Your Formby System Needs a Power Flush</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">In a larger Formby home, these signs are more financially significant than in a smaller property, more radiators, larger system, greater efficiency loss and a more expensive boiler to protect.</p>
      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Some of your larger Formby radiators cold at the bottom</strong><p>In a 4 or 5-bed Formby property, large bedroom or reception room radiators with cold patches at the bottom are the most visible sign of sludge build-up. These large radiators have more surface area at the bottom where magnetite settles and are often the first to show symptoms.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>One zone heating faster than the other in a multi-zone system</strong><p>In a Formby property with upstairs and downstairs zone control, if one zone heats significantly faster than the other, the slower zone likely has higher sludge contamination restricting flow. Each zone must be assessed and flushed individually.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Boiler making kettling or banging sounds</strong><p>Indicates debris in the system or localised boiling in the heat exchanger. In a relatively new Worcester Bosch or Vaillant installed in the last 5 to 10 years in Formby, kettling is often caused by sludge from the existing system that was not flushed before the new boiler was installed.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>House takes longer to reach temperature than it used to</strong><p>If your large Formby property used to be fully warm in 20 minutes and now takes 45 to 60 minutes, sludge restricting flow through the heat exchanger and radiators is the most likely cause. This is a significant efficiency loss on a large system.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Your boiler was installed on an existing system without a power flush</strong><p>One of the most important Formby cases. If a new Worcester Bosch or Vaillant was installed 3 to 7 years ago on your existing pipework and radiators without a power flush first, sludge from the old system may already be inside the new heat exchanger. A power flush now and a written report will both clean the system and provide evidence of maintenance for future warranty claims.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Heating bills disproportionately high for the property size</strong><p>A 14-radiator Formby system with 20% efficiency loss from sludge uses considerably more gas per season than the same system clean. If your bills are higher than you expect for the size of your house and boiler, system contamination is a strong candidate.</p></div></div>
      </div>
